What happens when you initialize a repository? Why do you need to do it?

	Initializing a repository makes it possible to use the git tools to 
	make e.g. commits and use version control. I need to do this, because
	otherwise all what I have learned in Lesson 1 would not be usable.

How is the staging area different from the working directory and the repository?
What value do you think it offers?

	Staging area is a temporary place for the files to be, before they are 'stored' in a commit. It offers you the freedom to combine different files in the commit.

